# Frontend Project Standards (Savorystream)

## Scope
- Apply these rules for work in `PROJET_PERSONNEL_P4_SAVORYSTREAM_FRONT_END`.

## React naming conventions

### Components
- Use PascalCase for all React components
  Example: UserCard.jsx, LoginForm.jsx

### Hooks
- Use camelCase starting with "use"
  Example: useAuth.js, useFetchArticles.js

### Functions
- Use camelCase
  Example: getUserData, formatDate

### Variables
- Use camelCase
  Example: userName, articleList

### Constants
- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
  Example: API_URL, MAX_RETRY_COUNT

### Files and folders
- Components folders: PascalCase
- Components files: PascalCase
- Other folders: camelCase
- Other files: camelCase

### General rules
- Keep naming descriptive and explicit
- Avoid abbreviations unless commonly understood
- Maintain consistency across the entire codebase
- For case-only renames, use two-step git moves:
  - `git mv path/Foo path/Foo_tmp && git mv path/Foo_tmp path/foo`
- Test MUST follow the same naming conventions as the source code they test

## Architecture and Reuse
- Prefer reusable shared components over duplication (especially forms and legal/footer blocks).
- Keep page components focused on orchestration; move repeated UI blocks into dedicated components.
- Keep pure logic in utils/hooks/services; keep rendering concerns in components.

## CORE CODE PRINCIPLES (MUST BE RESPECTED)

The following 5 principles MUST always be followed:

- Readability: code must be easy to read and understand at first glance
- Clear naming: all variables, functions, and components must have explicit and meaningful names
- Short functions: functions must remain small, focused, and do one thing only
- No duplication: avoid repeating logic; reuse existing functions or abstractions
- Single responsibility: each function, component, or module must have one clear responsibility

## ACCESSIBILITY (A11Y) — MANDATORY RULES

### General principle
- Accessibility is a first-class requirement, not an option
- Every UI feature must be usable without a mouse
- Prefer accessible native HTML before custom solutions

---

### Keyboard navigation
- All interactive elements must be reachable via keyboard (Tab / Shift+Tab)
- All actions must be usable via Enter and/or Space
- Focus order must follow visual order
- Visible focus indicator must always be present

---

### Semantic HTML
- Use semantic HTML elements first:
  - <button> for actions
  - <a> for navigation
  - <form>, <label>, <input> properly linked
- Do not use clickable <div> or <span> for interactive behavior
- Maintain correct heading hierarchy (h1 → h2 → h3)

---

### Forms
- Every input MUST have an associated <label>
- Errors must be shown as text, not only color
- Inputs and errors must be linked using aria-describedby when needed

---

### Visual accessibility
- Do not rely on color alone to communicate information (error, success, status)
- Maintain sufficient color contrast (WCAG AA minimum)
- Ensure layouts remain usable at 200% zoom

---

### ARIA usage
- Use ARIA only when semantic HTML is insufficient
- Avoid unnecessary or redundant ARIA attributes
- Every aria-label must be meaningful and descriptive
- Never replace proper HTML elements with ARIA roles

---

### Images & media
- All images must have meaningful alt text
- Decorative images must use alt=""
- Provide captions when applicable for video/audio content

---

### Focus management
- Focus must be managed after navigation or modal opening
- Modals must trap focus inside them
- Closing a modal must restore previous focus

---

### Rule enforcement
- Every UI change must be evaluated for accessibility impact
- If uncertain, choose the most accessible implementation by default

## TESTING RULES

### File structure
- Every created source file MUST have a corresponding test file
- Test files MUST be placed in a parallel structure to source files (mirror architecture)
- Test file naming must strictly match source file name with `.test` suffix

Example:
UserCard.jsx → UserCard.test.jsx
useAuth.js → useAuth.test.js
userService.js → userService.test.js

---

### Synchronization rule
- Any change in behavior MUST be reflected in the corresponding test file(s)
- Tests located in `src/tests` MUST always stay aligned with implementation

---

### Component testing strategy
- Component tests MUST focus on user-visible behavior only
- Always test:
  - Rendering (what the user sees)
  - User interactions (clicks, typing, navigation)
  - Observable side effects (UI updates, API-driven UI changes)
- NEVER test internal implementation details (state internals, private functions, hooks internals)

---

### Test structure (per file)
- Each test file MUST be organized in blocks per function or feature
- Start with the nominal case first
- Then describe edge cases and error cases progressively (one by one)

Example structure:
1. Nominal case (happy path)
2. Edge cases
3. Error handling cases

---

### Naming conventions
- All test names MUST be written in English
- Test names MUST describe user behavior clearly and explicitly
- Use descriptive sentences instead of technical wording

Example:
✔ should display user name when data is loaded
✘ test1 or renders correctly

## Change Safety
- After edits, run targeted tests for modified areas.
- Keep lints clean on touched files.
- Do not introduce root-level npm artifacts for this repo; npm dependencies belong to the frontend package.
